# Modes Archetype supports two generation modes. Pick based on your backend. ## Quick Comparison | | Full Stack | Headless | |---|---|---| | Use when | You own the database | API is external | | Database | SQLite, Postgres, MySQL | None | | Generates | Schema + Routers + Hooks | Services + Routers + Hooks | | Init command | | | --- ## Full Stack Mode You own the database. Archetype generates everything from schema to hooks. ### What you get ### Config example --- ## Headless Mode Database is external. You're connecting to a CMS, third-party API, or existing backend. ### What you get ### Config example ### Service layer Headless mode generates service stubs you fill in: --- ## When to use which ### Use Full Stack when: - Building a new app from scratch - You control the database - Using SQLite, Postgres, or MySQL ### Use Headless when: - Connecting to a headless CMS (Contentful, Sanity) - Consuming an existing REST/GraphQL API - Building a frontend for an existing backend - Deploying to edge/serverless without database access npx archetype init --yes npx archetype init --headless bash
npx archetype init --yes


### What you get


generated/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ db/schema.ts              ‚Üê Drizzle tables
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ schemas/product.ts        ‚Üê Zod validation
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ trpc/routers/             ‚Üê CRUD API
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ hooks/useProduct.ts       ‚Üê React Query hooks
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ tests/product.test.ts     ‚Üê Vitest tests
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ docs/openapi.json         ‚Üê API documentation
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ seeds/product.ts          ‚Üê Sample data
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ i18n/en/product.json      ‚Üê Translation keys


### Config example

 typescript
// archetype.config.ts
export default defineConfig({
  entities: [Product],
  database: {
    type: 'sqlite',       // or 'postgres', 'mysql'
    file: './sqlite.db',
  },
